```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_writer.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_reader.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

struct UserData {
    uint32_t user_id;
    std::string name;

    void serialise(auto& stream) {
        stream << user_id << name;
    }
};

void serialize_object(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, const UserData& data) {
    // Use const_cast because serialise() method is used for both reading and writing,
    // so it cannot be marked const even though it doesn't modify the object during serialization
    const_cast<UserData&>(data).serialise(writer);
}

void deserialize_object(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader& reader, UserData& data) {
    // The same serialise() method is used for deserialization
    // The reader will populate the object's members
    data.serialise(reader);
}
```

## Explanation:

1. **`serialize_object`**: This function serializes a `UserData` object by calling its `serialise()` method with the `binary_stream_writer`. The `const_cast` is necessary because the `serialise()` method cannot be `const` (it needs to support both reading and writing operations), even though it only reads from the object during serialization.

2. **`deserialize_object`**: This function deserializes a `UserData` object by calling the same `serialise()` method with the `binary_stream_reader`. The reader's `<<` operator will read from the stream and populate the object's members.

The unified `serialise()` method works with both writer and reader streams, using the same `<<` operator which behaves differently based on the stream type - writing data for writers and reading data for readers.

