# Complete Implementation

```cpp
#include <hexi/shared.h>
#include <cstring>
#include <cstddef>

using namespace hexi::detail;

bool check_regions_overlap(const void* src, std::size_t src_len, const void* dst, std::size_t dst_len) {
    // Handle edge cases - null pointers or zero-length regions don't overlap
    if (!src || !dst || src_len == 0 || dst_len == 0) {
        return false;
    }

    // Convert pointers to comparable addresses
    auto src_start = reinterpret_cast<std::uintptr_t>(src);
    auto dst_start = reinterpret_cast<std::uintptr_t>(dst);

    // Calculate end addresses (exclusive)
    auto src_end = src_start + src_len;
    auto dst_end = dst_start + dst_len;

    // Two memory regions overlap if:
    // - The source starts before the destination ends AND
    // - The destination starts before the source ends
    return (src_start < dst_end) && (dst_start < src_end);
}

bool safe_memory_copy(void* destination, const void* source, std::size_t length) {
    // Validate inputs
    if (!destination || !source || length == 0) {
        return false;
    }

    // Check for overlap between source and destination regions
    if (check_regions_overlap(source, length, destination, length)) {
        // Regions overlap - copy operation is unsafe
        // Using memcpy with overlapping regions causes undefined behavior
        return false;
    }

    // No overlap detected, safe to perform the copy
    std::memcpy(destination, source, length);
    return true;
}
```

## Explanation

**`check_regions_overlap` function:**
- Converts pointers to integer addresses for arithmetic comparison
- Calculates the end address of each region (start + length)
- Uses the standard overlap detection formula: two ranges `[a, b)` and `[c, d)` overlap if `a < d && c < b`
- Returns `false` for null pointers or zero-length regions (edge cases)

**`safe_memory_copy` function:**
- First validates that pointers are non-null and length is non-zero
- Calls `check_regions_overlap` to detect if source and destination overlap
- Returns `false` if overlap is detected (unsafe to use `memcpy`)
- Only performs the copy using `std::memcpy` when regions don't overlap
- Returns `true` on successful copy

This implementation ensures memory safety by preventing undefined behavior that would occur if `memcpy` were used on overlapping regions.

